The recipe is missing something...herbs! I added thyme and cayenne and it was great. I think sage would also well too. I have made variations of this many times and find it easy and tasty as a base recipe. Other changes I have made: butter instead of olive oil, extra garlic, balsamic vinegar instead of lemon, and cooking the squash in chicken stock (there are little 8 oz containers at trader joe's)

Rating: 2
I agree with other posters who found this bland. I made many of the suggestions to increase/deepen flavor but still was not very flavorful. Noone in the family liked it. I increased garlic, added leeks, used vegetable broth instead of water, and added toasted pine nuts. Once I tasted it, I even added a little blue cheese, which helped but still won't make it again.

Rating: 3
This is one of those recipes that is pretty good if you tweak it a bit. Spinach and onion pair so well with cheese, that you kind have to saute a large onion along with the squash, maybe with a little extra olive oil and some basil. A quarter to a half cup of chicken broth deepens the flavor of the squash if you use that instead of pasta water. I tossed in frozen spinach after the squash was already pretty well cooked (but not too soft!) Then if you also happen to have a little bit of extra mozarella lying around to toss in with the parmesan while your mixing in the pasta... Everyone likes this, including the kids. This is a tasty, healthy, and fast dinner (extra fast if you use frozen spinach) that includes your greens.

