Rating: 3
I baked the squash by cutting it in half and putting it face down. I used 1/2 of the squash for another recipe. I then cubed the squash and only put it in the dish to warm it after sauteeing the garlic and right before adding the spinach. I added pine nuts. Loved it -- light and delicious.

Rating: 3
I combined tips from the cook in Chicago (6/22/99) and added my own changes: I used gemelli. Added salt and pepper when sauteed squash. Sauteed the garlic in at the last 30 seconds of cooking the squash, just until it got fragrant, then added the spinach. Stirred in 1/4 cup lightly toasted pine nuts just before adding in the drained pasta. Omitted the lemon juice. Removed the completed dish from the heat and tossed in 2 tablespoons of a very flavorful Balsamic vinaigrette (2 parts olive oil to 1 part Balsamic vinegar, Dijon mustard and salt and pepper). Sprinkled with Parmesan just before serving. Delicious!

Rating: 3
This recipe reminded me of a salad that is made at Corner Bakery in Chicago. I used gemelli pasta and feta cheese instead of the parmesan. It's great hot or cold. The second time I made it, I omitted the lemon juice and after it cooled, tossed it with a balsamic vinaigrette and served it as a cold salad. Next time, I'm going to add pine nuts.

Rating: 2
A tip: I blanched the squash for a few minutes to make it easier to peel. The sweetness of the Butternut Squash is a little overwhelming when it is in such large pieces. I pureed some of the pieces together with some milk, which made a nice sauce. If I make it again I'd use about 1/2 the amount of squash and puree it all.